So how you doing?

68
00:05:21,012 --> 00:05:23,572
Not too bad, you know. Not too bad.

69
00:05:23,771 --> 00:05:25,966
l see you've become a pianist.

70
00:05:26,172 --> 00:05:28,605
Oh, yes, well, my friends call me that.

71
00:05:29,492 --> 00:05:31,925
How about you?
You still in the doctor business?

72
00:05:32,132 --> 00:05:36,011
You know what they say:
''Once a doctor, always a doctor. ''

73
00:05:36,211 --> 00:05:40,329
Yes, or in my case:
''Never a doctor, never a doctor. ''

74
00:05:41,132 --> 00:05:43,440
l never did understand
why you walked away.

75
00:05:44,172 --> 00:05:46,401
lt's a nice feeling. l do it a lot.

76
00:05:46,612 --> 00:05:47,761
Cheers.

77
00:05:48,331 --> 00:05:51,608
Excuse me.
Nick, l need you a minute.

78
00:05:51,812 --> 00:05:53,370
Be right with you.

79
00:05:53,572 --> 00:05:56,132
l gotta go do something.
lf l don't catch you later. . .

80
00:05:56,331 --> 00:05:59,961
. . .l'll be down at the Village
for two weeks at the Sonata Cafe.

81
00:06:00,172 --> 00:06:02,732
-Stop by if you get a chance.
-l'll be there.

82
00:06:03,531 --> 00:06:06,365
-lt's great seeing you.
-Good seeing you too, man.

83
00:06:46,172 --> 00:06:49,447
l think that's my glass.

84
00:06:49,651 --> 00:06:52,644
l' m absolutely certain of it.

85
00:07:06,091 --> 00:07:09,925
My name is Sandor Szavost.
l' m Hungarian.

86
00:07:20,131 --> 00:07:22,441
My name is Alice Harford.

87
00:07:22,772 --> 00:07:24,727
l' m American.

88
00:07:25,371 --> 00:07:27,202
Delighted to meet you, Alice.

89
00:07:28,731 --> 00:07:33,283
Did you ever read the Latin poet Ovid
on The Art of Love?

90
00:07:35,331 --> 00:07:38,802
Didn't he wind up all by himself. . .

91
00:07:39,412 --> 00:07:41,642
. . .crying his eyes out. . .

92
00:07:41,851 --> 00:07:45,447
. . .in some place
with a very bad climate?

93
00:07:46,611 --> 00:07:49,409
But he also had a good time first.

94
00:07:49,851 --> 00:07:52,081
A very good time.

95
00:07:54,451 --> 00:07:57,125
Are you here
with anyone tonight, Alice?

96
00:08:00,131 --> 00:08:02,087
With my husband.

97
00:08:02,412 --> 00:08:04,288
Oh, how sad.

98
00:08:04,971 --> 00:08:09,682
But then l' m sure he's the sort of man
who wouldn't mind if we danced.

99
00:08:14,331 --> 00:08:16,447
What do you do, Alice?

100
00:08:16,971 --> 00:08:20,202
Well, at the moment. . .

101
00:08:20,971 --> 00:08:23,246
. . .l' m looking for a job.

102
00:08:24,371 --> 00:08:27,966
l used to manage
an art gallery in SoHo.

103
00:08:28,611 --> 00:08:30,648
But it went broke.

104
00:08:32,652 --> 00:08:34,130
What a shame.

105
00:08:35,772 --> 00:08:38,206
l have some friends in the art game.

106
00:08:38,851 --> 00:08:40,967
Perhaps l can be of some help.

107
00:08:44,572 --> 00:08:46,163
Thank you.

108
00:09:04,572 --> 00:09:06,129
Someone you know?

109
00:09:09,851 --> 00:09:11,443
My. . .

110
00:09:11,971 --> 00:09:13,451
. . .husband.

111
00:09:17,932 --> 00:09:20,844
Don't you think
one of the charms of marriage. . .

112
00:09:21,091 --> 00:09:25,528
. . .is that it makes deception
a necessity for both parties?

113
00:09:29,292 --> 00:09:31,759
May l ask why a beautiful woman. . .

114
00:09:32,251 --> 00:09:35,767
. . .who could have any man in this room,
wants to be married?

115
00:09:38,611 --> 00:09:40,523
Why wouldn't she?

116
00:09:42,251 --> 00:09:44,243
ls it as bad as that?

117
00:09:45,491 --> 00:09:47,767
As good as that.

118
00:09:48,491 --> 00:09:50,163
Do you know Nuala Windsor?

119
00:09:50,371 --> 00:09:54,808
No, and it's very lovely
to meet you both.

120
00:09:56,731 --> 00:09:58,687
How do you spell Nuala?

121
00:09:59,292 --> 00:10:04,001
N-U-A-L-A.

122
00:10:05,692 --> 00:10:08,331
You don't remember me, do you?

123
00:10:09,451 --> 00:10:11,919
You were very kind to me once.

124
00:10:12,131 --> 00:10:15,726
Only once?
That sounds like a terrible oversight!

125
00:10:17,052 --> 00:10:21,091
l was doing a photo session
in Rockefeller Plaza. . .

126
00:10:21,292 --> 00:10:22,804
. . .on a very windy day. . .?

127
00:10:23,011 --> 00:10:27,051
-And you got something in your eye.
-Just about half of Fifth Avenue.

128
00:10:27,451 --> 00:10:30,807
You were such a gentleman!
You gave me your handkerchief. . .

129
00:10:31,052 --> 00:10:33,407
. . .which was also clean.

130
00:10:35,011 --> 00:10:38,561
That is the kind of hero
l can be sometimes.

131
00:10:39,491 --> 00:10:42,484
You know why women used to get married,
don't you?

132
00:10:43,971 --> 00:10:46,087
Why don't you tell me?

133
00:10:47,772 --> 00:10:50,605
lt was the only way they could
lose their virginity. . .

134
00:10:51,011 --> 00:10:54,447
. . .and be free to do
what they wanted with other men.

135
00:10:55,451 --> 00:10:57,567
The ones they really wanted.

136
00:11:02,052 --> 00:11:03,962
Fascinating.

137
00:11:07,772 --> 00:11:11,366
Do you know what's so nice
about doctors?

138
00:11:12,932 --> 00:11:16,288
Usually a lot less than people imagine.

139
00:11:17,932 --> 00:11:20,446
They always seem so. . .

140
00:11:21,331 --> 00:11:22,811
. . .knowledgeable.

141
00:11:23,772 --> 00:11:27,447
Oh, they are very knowledgeable. . .

142
00:11:27,652 --> 00:11:30,404
. . .about all sorts of things.

143
00:11:32,292 --> 00:11:34,327
But l bet they work too hard.

144
00:11:34,812 --> 00:11:38,441
Just think of all they miss.

145
00:11:39,331 --> 00:11:41,562
You' re probably right.

146
00:11:42,532 --> 00:11:47,128
Ladies, where exactly are we going?

147
00:11:47,772 --> 00:11:49,250
Exactly?

148
00:11:51,611 --> 00:11:54,046
Where the rainbow ends.

149
00:11:54,611 --> 00:11:56,408
Where the rainbow ends?

150
00:11:56,611 --> 00:11:59,922
Don't you want to go
where the rainbow ends?

151
00:12:00,131 --> 00:12:03,090
Now that depends where that is.

152
00:12:03,292 --> 00:12:04,884
Well, let's find out.

153
00:12:05,091 --> 00:12:07,811
Excuse me, ladies.
Sorry, Dr. Harford.

154
00:12:08,052 --> 00:12:12,125
Could you come with me for a moment?
Something for Mr. Ziegler.

155
00:12:14,371 --> 00:12:15,486
Fine.

156
00:12:17,172 --> 00:12:18,524
To be continued?

157
00:12:40,412 --> 00:12:42,403
Bill, thanks for coming.

158
00:12:44,331 --> 00:12:47,085
We had a little accident here.

159
00:12:47,451 --> 00:12:48,770
What happened?

160
00:12:49,292 --> 00:12:51,123
Well, she was. . . .

161
00:12:51,611 --> 00:12:55,605
